"{\"uid\": \"citizen.co.za-lifestyle-entertainment-bucie-returns-home-after-entertaining-sa-athletes-at-paris-2024-olympics\", \"text\": \"Home\\u00bbEntertainment  ByBonginkosi Tiwane  9 minute read  7 August 2024  11:43 am  Bucie was recently at the Paris 2024  Olympics to perform for South African athletes. Picture: Supplied  Like food, music is one of those things that capture the feeling of home without one being physically there.  Singer Bucie gave South African athletes a taste of home when she performed for them at the ongoing Paris 2024 Olympics.  \\\"I was invited to sing for the South African athletes and their families as a way of making them feel at home, even when they are far away,\\\" Bucie toldThe Citizenafter returning to Mzansi.  TheSupermansinger was invited by the Department of Sports, Arts and Culture to be part of the Ekhaya is a Home away from Home activities.  Ekhaya is a Home away from Home is an abode for South Africans to meet, connect, and network while promoting everything South African, during the Paris Olympics.  A post shared by Bucie \\ud83c\\uddff\\ud83c\\udde6\\ud83d\\udc51 (@bucie_nkomo)  There have been daily activities at the hub and people are encouraged to come and see what South Africa has to offer and watch the games live at the centre. The centre is open daily from 11am until 11pm.  Unlike US rapper Snoop Dogg, Bucie did not stay at the Olympics for its duration nor get to cheer on the athletes competing from the sidelines.  \\\"Though I did not go to the stadium, I experienced the incredible spirit in the streets and at fan parks around the city. Their 'gees' is amazing, but I have to say, it will never touch our 'Phillip'!\\\"  ALSO READ:Snoop Dogg earns around R150m for Paris 2024 Olympics presence - report  Before heading to Paris, Bucie hosted an intimate two-night performance in Rosebank's Flute Live. The performances were sold-out, with her fans eagerly wanting to see her live since they had not in a long while.  \\\"The energy from the fans was incredibly healing and uplifting. Their love and support truly filled my soul and reminded me of why I do what I do,\\\" averred Bucie.  \\\"The truth is that I never really stopped performing,\\\" she said.  \\\"I had regular continental and international performances during my hiatus. I headlined a sold-out festival in Angola just this past June. A funny (maybe not at the time) story is how I almost got stuck in Canada just before the lockdown - I literally made it back by a day.\\\"  The last few months have not been the smoothest for thesinger-songwriter, with reports of her marriage being in tatters, which has led to an allegeddivorcefrom her husband. But speaking to this publication, Bucie was rather cagey about speaking on the state of her marriage.  \\\"I have never discussed the state of my marriage publicly, even though South Africans felt it was okay to speculate about it. It is a sacred part of my life that I do not bring into the entertainment space.\\\"  ALSO READ:Convicted Kwaito artist Brickz graduates while serving 15-year jail sentence  The 37-year-old vocalist released a new single in May titledFaithfuland said the ditty is a testament to how she has lived her life.  A post shared by Bucie \\ud83c\\uddff\\ud83c\\udde6\\ud83d\\udc51 (@bucie_nkomo)  \\\"Creating music for me has always been about conveying the good word, which is essentially what gospel is. I sing about love - love is the good word. So, yes, my music will continue to carry that essence.\\\"  NOW READ:Stars align for drama: MasterChef SA's astrology challenge claims its 2nd victim  Add The Citizen as a Preferred Source on Google and follow us on Google News to see more of our trusted reporting in Google News and Top Stories.  Download our app  Get the latest news and updates on Whatsapp  The latest news directly in your inbox  Support Local Journalism  2026 The Citizen. All Rights Reserved.\"}"